# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acidobacteriota
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The genes coding for it are referred to as **16S rRNA genes** and are used in reconstructing phylogenies, due to the slow rates of evolution of this region of the gene.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Fox were two of the people who pioneered the use of 16S rRNA in phylogenetics in 1977.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Multiple sequences of the 16S rRNA gene can exist within a single bacterium.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The descriptor *16S* refers to the size of these ribosomal subunits as reflected indirectly by the speed at which they sediment when samples are centrifuged.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The 16S rRNA gene is used for phylogenetic studies as it is highly conserved between different species of bacteria and archaea.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Carl Woese pioneered this use of 16S rRNA in 1977.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] It is suggested that 16S rRNA gene can be used as a reliable molecular clock because 16S rRNA sequences from distantly related bacterial lineages are shown to have similar functionalities.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Some thermophilic archaea (e.g. order Thermoproteales) contain 16S rRNA gene introns that are located in highly conserved regions and can impact the annealing of "universal" primers.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Mitochondrial and chloroplastic rRNA are also amplified.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The most common primer pair was devised by Weisburg *et al.* (1991) and is currently referred to as 27F and 1492R; however, for some applications shorter amplicons may be necessary, for example for 454 sequencing with titanium chemistry the primer pair 27F-534R covering V1 to V3.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The two primers are almost identical, but 27F has an M instead of a C.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] AGAGTTTGATC**M**TGGCTCAG compared with 8F.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] In addition to highly conserved primer binding sites, 16S rRNA gene sequences contain hypervariable regions that can provide species-specific signature sequences useful for identification of bacteria.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] As a result, 16S rRNA gene sequencing has become prevalent in medical microbiology as a rapid and cheap alternative to phenotypic methods of bacterial identification.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Although it was originally used to identify bacteria, 16S sequencing was subsequently found to be capable of reclassifying bacteria into completely new species, or even genera.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] It has also been used to describe new species that have never been successfully cultured.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] With third-generation sequencing coming to many labs, simultaneous identification of thousands of 16S rRNA sequences is possible within hours, allowing metagenomic studies, for example of gut flora.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] In samples collected from patients with confirmed infections, 16S rRNA next-generation sequencing (NGS) demonstrated enhanced detection in 40% of cases compared to traditional culture methods; moreover, pre-sampling antibiotic consumption did not significantly affect the sensitivity of 16S NGS.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The bacterial 16S gene contains nine hypervariable regions (V1–V9), ranging from about 30 to 100 base pairs long, that are involved in the secondary structure of the small ribosomal subunit.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The degree of conservation varies widely between hypervariable regions, with more conserved regions correlating to higher-level taxonomy and less conserved regions to lower levels, such as genus and species.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] While the entire 16S sequence allows for comparison of all hypervariable regions, at approximately 1,500 base pairs long it can be prohibitively expensive for studies seeking to identify or characterize diverse bacterial communities.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] These studies commonly utilize the Illumina platform, which produces reads at rates 50-fold and 12,000-fold less expensive than 454 pyrosequencing and Sanger sequencing, respectively.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] While cheaper and allowing for deeper community coverage, Illumina sequencing only produces reads 75–250 base pairs long (up to 300 base pairs with Illumina MiSeq), and has no established protocol for reliably assembling the full gene in community samples.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Full hypervariable regions can be assembled from a single Illumina run, however, making them ideal targets for the platform.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] While 16S hypervariable regions can vary dramatically between bacteria, the 16S gene as a whole maintains greater length homogeneity than its eukaryotic counterpart (18S ribosomal RNA), which can make alignments easier.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Additionally, the 16S gene contains highly conserved sequences between hypervariable regions, enabling the design of universal primers that can reliably produce the same sections of the 16S sequence across different taxa.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Although no hypervariable region can accurately classify all bacteria from domain to species, some can reliably predict specific taxonomic levels.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Many community studies select semi-conserved hypervariable regions like the V4 for this reason, as it can provide resolution at the phylum level as accurately as the full 16S gene.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] While lesser-conserved regions struggle to classify new species when higher order taxonomy is unknown, they are often used to detect the presence of specific pathogens.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] In one study by Chakravorty et al. in 2007, the authors characterized the V1–V8 regions of a variety of pathogens in order to determine which hypervariable regions would be most useful to include for disease-specific and broad assays.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Amongst other findings, they noted that the V3 region was best at identifying the genus for all pathogens tested, and that V6 was the most accurate at differentiating species between all CDC-watched pathogens tested, including anthrax.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] While 16S hypervariable region analysis is a powerful tool for bacterial taxonomic studies, it struggles to differentiate between closely related species.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] In the families *Enterobacteriaceae*, *Clostridiaceae*, and *Peptostreptococcaceae*, species can share up to 99% sequence similarity across the full 16S gene.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] As a result, the V4 sequences can differ by only a few nucleotides, leaving reference databases unable to reliably classify these bacteria at lower taxonomic levels.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] By limiting 16S analysis to select hypervariable regions, these studies can fail to observe differences in closely related taxa and group them into single taxonomic units, therefore underestimating the total diversity of the sample.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Furthermore, bacterial genomes can house multiple 16S genes, with the V1, V2, and V6 regions containing the greatest intraspecies diversity.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] While not the most precise method of classifying bacterial species, analysis of the hypervariable regions remains one of the most useful tools available to bacterial community studies.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Under the assumption that evolution is driven by vertical transmission, 16S rRNA genes have long been believed to be species-specific, and infallible as genetic markers inferring phylogenetic relationships among prokaryotes.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] However, a growing number of observations suggest the occurrence of horizontal transfer of these genes.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] In addition to observations of natural occurrence, transferability of these genes is supported experimentally using a specialized *Escherichia coli* genetic system.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Using a null mutant of *E. coli* as host, growth of the mutant strain was shown to be complemented by foreign 16S rRNA genes that were phylogenetically distinct from *E. coli* at the phylum level.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Such functional compatibility was also seen in *Thermus thermophilus*.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Furthermore, in *T. thermophilus*, both complete and partial gene transfer was observed.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Partial transfer resulted in spontaneous generation of apparently random chimera between host and foreign bacterial genes.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Thus, 16S rRNA genes may have evolved through multiple mechanisms, including vertical inheritance and horizontal gene transfer; the frequency of the latter may be much higher than previously thought.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The 16S rRNA gene is used as the standard for classification and identification of microbes, because it is present in most microbes and shows proper changes.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Type strains of 16S rRNA gene sequences for most bacteria and archaea are available on public databases, such as NCBI.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] However, the quality of the sequences found on these databases is often not validated.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Therefore, secondary databases that collect only 16S rRNA sequences are widely used.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] SILVA provides comprehensive, quality checked and regularly updated datasets of aligned small (16S/18S, SSU) and large subunit (23S/28S, LSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences for all three domains of life as well as a suite of search, primer-design and alignment tools (Bacteria, Archaea and Eukarya).
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] GreenGenes is a quality controlled, comprehensive 16S rRNA gene reference database and taxonomy based on a *de novo* phylogeny that provides standard operational taxonomic unit sets.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] EzBioCloud database, formerly known as EzTaxon, consists of a complete hierarchical taxonomic system containing 62,988 bacteria and archaea species/phylotypes which includes 15,290 valid published names as of September 2018.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Based on the phylogenetic relationship such as maximum-likelihood and OrthoANI, all species/subspecies are represented by at least one 16S rRNA gene sequence.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The EzBioCloud database is systematically curated and updated regularly which also includes novel candidate species.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Moreover, the website provides bioinformatics tools such as ANI calculator, ContEst16S and 16S rRNA DB for QIIME and Mothur pipeline.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] MIMt is a compact non-redundant 16S database for a rapid metagenomic samples identification.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] It is composed of 48,749 full 16S sequences belonging to 24,626 well classified bacteria and archaea species.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] All sequences were obtained from complete genomes deposited in NCBI and for each of the sequences full taxonomic hierarchy is provided.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] It contains no redundancy, so only one representative for each species was considered avoiding same sequences from different strains, isolates or pathovars resulting in a very fast tool for microorganisms identification, compatible with any classification software (QIIME, Mothur, DADA, etc).
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The Ribosomal Database Project (RDP) was a curated database that offers ribosome data along with related programs and services.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The offerings included phylogenetically ordered alignments of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences, derived phylogenetic trees, rRNA secondary structure diagrams and various software packages for handling, analyzing and displaying alignments and trees.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] Due to its large size the RDP database is often used as the basis for bioinformatic tool development and creating manually curated databases.
[src:acidobacteriota/16s-rrna] The RDP server was taken offline in 2023, but the software is still available for download.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The **abiogenic petroleum origin** hypothesis proposes that most of Earth's petroleum and natural gas deposits were formed inorganically, commonly known as **abiotic oil**.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Scientific evidence overwhelmingly supports a biogenic origin for most of the world's petroleum deposits.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Mainstream theories about the formation of hydrocarbons on Earth point to an origin from the decomposition of long-dead organisms, though the existence of hydrocarbons on extraterrestrial bodies like Saturn's moon Titan indicates that hydrocarbons are sometimes naturally produced by inorganic means.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A historical overview of theories of the abiogenic origins of hydrocarbons has been published.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold's "deep gas hypothesis" proposes that some natural gas deposits were formed out of hydrocarbons deep in the Earth's mantle.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Earlier studies of mantle-derived rocks from many places have shown that hydrocarbons from the mantle region can be found widely around the globe.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, the concentration of such hydrocarbons is low.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] While there may be large deposits of abiotic hydrocarbons, globally significant amounts of abiotic hydrocarbons are deemed unlikely.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some abiogenic hypotheses have proposed that oil and gas did not originate from fossil deposits, but have instead originated from deep carbon deposits, present since the formation of the Earth.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The abiogenic hypothesis regained some support in 2009 when researchers at the KTH Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm reported they believed they had proven that fossils from animals and plants are not necessary for crude oil and natural gas to be generated.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abiogenic hypotheses were revived in the last half of the 20th century by Soviet scientists who had little influence outside the Soviet Union because most of their research was published in Russian.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The hypothesis was re-defined and made popular in the West by astronomer Thomas Gold, a prominent proponent of the abiogenic hypothesis, who developed his theories from 1979 to 1998 and published his research in English.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abraham Gottlob Werner and the proponents of neptunism in the 18th century regarded basaltic sills as solidified oils or bitumen.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] While these notions proved unfounded, the basic idea of an association between petroleum and magmatism persisted.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Von Humboldt proposed an inorganic abiogenic hypothesis for petroleum formation after he observed petroleum springs in the Bay of Cumaux (Cumaná) on the northeast coast of Venezuela.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] He is quoted as saying, "the petroleum is the product of a distillation from great depth and issues from the primitive rocks beneath which the forces of all volcanic action lie".
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Other early prominent proponents of what would become the generalized abiogenic hypothesis included Dmitri Mendeleev and Berthelot.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1951, the Soviet geologist Nikolai Alexandrovitch Kudryavtsev proposed the modern abiotic hypothesis of petroleum.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] On the basis of his analysis of the Athabasca Oil Sands in Alberta, Canada, he concluded that no "source rocks" could form the enormous volume of hydrocarbons, and therefore offered abiotic deep petroleum as the most plausible explanation.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] (Humic coals have since been proposed for the source rocks.) Others who continued Kudryavtsev's work included Petr N.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Following Thomas Gold's death in 2004, Jack Kenney of Gas Resources Corporation has recently come into prominence as a proponent of the theories, supported by studies by researchers at the Royal Institute of Technology (KTH) in Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Within the mantle, carbon may exist as hydrocarbons—chiefly methane—and as elemental carbon, carbon dioxide, and carbonates.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abiogenic hypotheses generally reject the supposition that certain molecules found within petroleum, known as biomarkers, are indicative of the biological origin of petroleum.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] As of 2009, little research is directed towards establishing abiogenic petroleum or methane, although the Carnegie Institution for Science has reported that ethane and heavier hydrocarbons can be synthesized under conditions of the upper mantle.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Research mostly related to astrobiology and the deep microbial biosphere and serpentinite reactions, however, continues to provide insight into the contribution of abiogenic hydrocarbons into petroleum accumulations.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold's work was focused on hydrocarbon deposits of primordial origin.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Meteorites are believed to represent the major composition of material from which the Earth was formed.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some meteorites, such as carbonaceous chondrites, contain carbonaceous material.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] If a large amount of this material is still within the Earth, it could have been leaking upward for billions of years.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The thermodynamic conditions within the mantle would allow many hydrocarbon molecules to be at equilibrium under high pressure and high temperature.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Although molecules in these conditions may disassociate, resulting fragments would be reformed due to the pressure.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] An average equilibrium of various molecules would exist depending upon conditions and the carbon-hydrogen ratio of the material.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Russian researchers concluded that hydrocarbon mixes would be created within the mantle.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Experiments under high temperatures and pressures produced many hydrocarbons—including n-alkanes through C10H22—from iron oxide, calcium carbonate, and water.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Because such materials are in the mantle and in subducted crust, there is no requirement that all hydrocarbons be produced from primordial deposits.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Hydrogen gas and water have been found more than 6,000 metres (20,000 ft) deep in the upper crust in the Siljan Ring boreholes and the Kola Superdeep Borehole.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Data from the western United States suggests that aquifers from near the surface may extend to depths of 10,000 metres (33,000 ft) to 20,000 metres (66,000 ft).
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Hydrogen gas can be created by water reacting with silicates, quartz, and feldspar at temperatures in the range of 25 °C (77 °F) to 270 °C (518 °F).
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] These minerals are common in crustal rocks such as granite.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Hydrogen may react with dissolved carbon compounds in water to form methane and higher carbon compounds.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The above reaction operates best at low pressures.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] At pressures greater than 5 gigapascals (49,000 atm), almost no hydrogen is formed.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold reported that hydrocarbons were found in the Siljan Ring borehole and in general increased with depth, although the venture was not a commercial success.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, several geologists analysed the results and said that no hydrocarbon was found.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1967, the Soviet scientist Emmanuil B.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Chekaliuk proposed that petroleum could be formed at high temperatures and pressures from inorganic carbon in the form of carbon dioxide, hydrogen or methane.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This mechanism is supported by several lines of evidence which are accepted by modern scientific literature.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This involves synthesis of oil within the crust via catalysis by chemically reductive rocks.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A proposed mechanism for the formation of inorganic hydrocarbons is via natural analogs of the Fischer–Tropsch process known as the *serpentinite mechanism* or the serpentinite process.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Serpentinites are ideal rocks to host this process as they are formed from peridotites and dunites, rocks which contain greater than 80% olivine and usually a percentage of Fe-Ti spinel minerals.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Most olivines also contain high nickel concentrations (up to several percent) and may also contain chromite or chromium as a contaminant in olivine, providing the needed transition metals.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, serpentinite synthesis and spinel cracking reactions require hydrothermal alteration of pristine peridotite-dunite, which is a finite process intrinsically related to metamorphism, and further, requires significant addition of water.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Serpentinite is unstable at mantle temperatures and is readily dehydrated to granulite, amphibolite, talc–schist and even eclogite.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This suggests that methanogenesis in the presence of serpentinites is restricted in space and time to mid-ocean ridges and upper levels of subduction zones.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, water has been found as deep as 12,000 metres (39,000 ft), so water-based reactions are dependent upon the local conditions.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Oil being created by this process in intracratonic regions is limited by the materials and temperature.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A chemical basis for the abiotic petroleum process is the serpentinization of peridotite, beginning with methanogenesis via hydrolysis of olivine into serpentine in the presence of carbon dioxide.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Olivine, composed of Forsterite and Fayalite metamorphoses into serpentine, magnetite and silica by the following reactions, with silica from fayalite decomposition (reaction 1a) feeding into the forsterite reaction (1b).
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] When this reaction occurs in the presence of dissolved carbon dioxide (carbonic acid) at temperatures above 500 °C (932 °F) Reaction 2a takes place.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The upgrading of methane to higher n-alkane hydrocarbons is via dehydrogenation of methane in the presence of catalyst transition metals (e.g.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Magnetite, chromite and ilmenite are Fe-spinel group minerals found in many rocks but rarely as a major component in non-ultramafic rocks.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In these rocks, high concentrations of magmatic magnetite, chromite and ilmenite provide a reduced matrix which may allow abiotic cracking of methane to higher hydrocarbons during hydrothermal events.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Chemically reduced rocks are required to drive this reaction and high temperatures are required to allow methane to be polymerized to ethane.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Note that reaction 1a, above, also creates magnetite.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Reaction 3 results in n-alkane hydrocarbons, including linear saturated hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes, ketones, aromatics, and cyclic compounds.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Note that CaO (lime) is not a mineral species found within natural rocks.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Whilst this reaction is possible, it is not plausible.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The "deep biotic petroleum hypothesis", similar to the abiogenic petroleum origin hypothesis, holds that not all petroleum deposits within the Earth's rocks can be explained purely according to the orthodox view of petroleum geology.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold used the term "the deep hot biosphere" to describe the microbes which live underground.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This hypothesis is different from biogenic oil in that the role of deep-dwelling microbes is a biological source for oil which is not of a sedimentary origin and is not sourced from surface carbon.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Deep microbial life is only a contaminant of primordial hydrocarbons.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Parts of microbes yield molecules as biomarkers.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Deep biotic oil is considered to be formed as a byproduct of the life cycle of deep microbes.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Shallow biotic oil is considered to be formed as a byproduct of the life cycles of shallow microbes.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold, in a 1999 book, cited the discovery of thermophile bacteria in the Earth's crust as new support for the postulate that these bacteria could explain the existence of certain biomarkers in extracted petroleum.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A rebuttal of biogenic origins based on biomarkers has been offered by Kenney, et al.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Methane is ubiquitous in crustal fluid and gas.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Research continues to attempt to characterise crustal sources of methane as biogenic or abiogenic using carbon isotope fractionation of observed gases (Lollar & Sherwood 2006).
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] One argument for abiogenic oil cites the high carbon depletion of methane as stemming from the observed carbon isotope depletion with depth in the crust.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, diamonds, which are definitively of mantle origin, are not as depleted as methane, which implies that methane carbon isotope fractionation is not controlled by mantle values.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Commercially extractable concentrations of helium (greater than 0.3%) are present in natural gas from the Panhandle-Hugoton fields in the US, as well as from some Algerian and Russian gas fields.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Helium trapped within most petroleum occurrences, such as the occurrence in Texas, is of a distinctly crustal character with an *Ra* ratio of less than 0.0001 that of the atmosphere.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Certain chemicals found in naturally occurring petroleum contain chemical and structural similarities to compounds found within many living organisms.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] These include terpenoids, terpenes, pristane, phytane, cholestane, chlorins and porphyrins, which are large, chelating molecules in the same family as heme and chlorophyll.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Materials which suggest certain biological processes include tetracyclic diterpane and oleanane.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The presence of these chemicals in crude oil is a result of the inclusion of biological material in the oil; these chemicals are released by kerogen during the production of hydrocarbon oils, as these are chemicals highly resistant to degradation and plausible chemical paths have been studied.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abiotic defenders state that biomarkers get into oil during its way up as it gets in touch with ancient fossils.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However a more plausible explanation is that biomarkers are traces of biological molecules from bacteria (archaea) that feed on primordial hydrocarbons and die in that environment.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] For example, hopanoids are just parts of the bacterial cell wall present in oil as a contaminant.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Nickel (Ni), vanadium (V), lead (Pb), arsenic (As), cadmium (Cd), mercury (Hg) and others metals frequently occur in oils.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some heavy crude oils, such as Venezuelan heavy crude have up to 45% vanadium pentoxide content in their ash, high enough that it is a commercial source for vanadium.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abiotic supporters argue that these metals are common in Earth's mantle, but relatively high contents of nickel, vanadium, lead and arsenic can be usually found in almost all marine sediments.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Analysis of 22 trace elements in oils correlate significantly better with chondrite, serpentinized fertile mantle peridotite, and the primitive mantle than with oceanic or continental crust, and shows no correlation with seawater.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Sir Robert Robinson studied the chemical makeup of natural petroleum oils in great detail, and concluded that they were mostly far too hydrogen-rich to be a likely product of the decay of plant debris, assuming a dual origin for Earth hydrocarbons.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, several processes which generate hydrogen could supply kerogen hydrogenation which is compatible with the conventional explanation.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Olefins, the unsaturated hydrocarbons, would have been expected to predominate by far in any material that was derived in that way.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This hypothesis was later demonstrated to have been a misunderstanding by Robinson, related to the fact that only short duration experiments were available to him.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Olefins are thermally very unstable (which is why natural petroleum normally does not contain such compounds) and in laboratory experiments that last more than a few hours, the olefins are no longer present.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The presence of low-oxygen and hydroxyl-poor hydrocarbons in natural living media is supported by the presence of natural waxes (n=30+), oils (n=20+) and lipids in both plant matter and animal matter, for instance fats in phytoplankton, zooplankton and so on.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] These oils and waxes, however, occur in quantities too small to significantly affect the overall hydrogen/carbon ratio of biological materials.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, after the discovery of highly aliphatic biopolymers in algae, and that oil generating kerogen essentially represents concentrates of such materials, no theoretical problem exists anymore.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Also, the millions of source rock samples that have been analyzed for petroleum yield by the petroleum industry have confirmed the large quantities of petroleum found in sedimentary basins.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Occurrences of abiotic petroleum in commercial amounts in the oil wells in offshore Vietnam are sometimes cited, as well as in the Eugene Island block 330 oil field, and the Dnieper-Donets Basin.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, the origins of all these wells can also be explained with the biotic theory.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Modern geologists think that commercially profitable deposits of abiotic petroleum *could* be found, but no current deposit has convincing evidence that it originated from abiotic sources.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The Soviet school of thought saw evidence of their hypothesis in the fact that some oil reservoirs exist in non-sedimentary rocks such as granite, metamorphic or porous volcanic rocks.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, opponents noted that non-sedimentary rocks served as reservoirs for biologically originated oil expelled from nearby sedimentary source rock through common migration or re-migration mechanisms.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The Lost City hydrothermal field was determined to have abiogenic hydrocarbon production.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Proskurowski et al. wrote, "Radiocarbon evidence rules out seawater bicarbonate as the carbon source for FTT reactions, suggesting that a mantle-derived inorganic carbon source is leached from the host rocks.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, some geochemists concluded by geochemical analysis that the oil in the seeps came from the organic-rich Ordovician Tretaspis shale, where it was heated by the meteorite impact.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1986–1990, the Gravberg-1 borehole was drilled through the deepest rock in the Siljan Ring in which proponents had hoped to find hydrocarbon reservoirs.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] It stopped at the depth of 6,800 metres (22,300 ft) due to drilling problems, after private investors spent $40 million.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This well also sampled over 13,000 feet (4,000 m) of methane-bearing inclusions.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1991–1992, a second borehole, Stenberg-1, was drilled a few miles away to a depth of 6,500 metres (21,300 ft), finding similar results.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Direct observation of bacterial mats and fracture-fill carbonate and humin of bacterial origin in deep boreholes in Australia are also taken as evidence for the abiogenic origin of petroleum.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Panhandle-Hugoton field (Anadarko Basin) in the south-central United States is the most important gas field with commercial helium content.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some abiogenic proponents interpret this as evidence that both the helium and the natural gas came from the mantle.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The Bạch Hổ oil field in Vietnam has been proposed as an example of abiogenic oil because it is 4,000 m of fractured basement granite, at a depth of 5,000 m.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, others argue that it contains biogenic oil which leaked into the basement horst from conventional source rocks within the Cửu Long basin.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A major component of mantle-derived carbon is indicated in commercial gas reservoirs in the Pannonian and Vienna basins of Hungary and Austria.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Natural gas pools interpreted as being mantle-derived are the Shengli Field and Songliao Basin, northeastern China.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The Chimaera gas seep, near Çıralı, Antalya (southwest Turkey), has been continuously active for millennia and it is known to be the source of the first Olympic fire in the Hellenistic period.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Local geology of Chimaera flames, at exact position of flames, reveals contact between serpentinized ophiolite and carbonate rocks.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Fischer–Tropsch process can be suitable reaction to form hydrocarbon gases.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] What unites both theories of oil origin is the low success rate in predicting the locations of giant oil/gas fields: according to the statistics discovering a giant demands drilling 500+ exploration wells.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A team of American-Russian scientists (mathematicians, geologists, geophysicists, and computer scientists) developed an Artificial Intelligence software and the appropriate technology for geological applications, and used it for predicting places of giant oil/gas deposits.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1986, the team published a prognostic map for discovering giant oil and gas fields at the Andes in South America based on abiogenic petroleum origin theory.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Yury Pikovsky (Moscow State University) assumes that petroleum moves from the mantle to the surface through permeable channels created at the intersection of deep faults.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The technology uses 1) maps of morphostructural zoning, which outlines the morphostructural nodes (intersections of faults), and 2) pattern recognition program that identify nodes containing giant oil/gas fields.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] It was forecast that eleven nodes, which had not been developed at that time, contain giant oil or gas fields.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] These 11 sites covered only 8% of the total area of all the Andes basins.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] 30 years later (in 2018) was published the result of comparing the prognosis and the reality.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Since the publication of the prognostic map in 1986, six giant oil/gas fields were discovered in the Andes region: Caño Limón oilfield, Cusiana, Capiagua, Colombia, and Volcanera (Llanos basin, Colombia), Camisea (Ukayali basin, Peru), and Incahuasi (Chaco basin, Bolivia).
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] All discoveries were made in places shown on the 1986 prognostic map as promising areas.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] During the 1960s, Donald Hings was issued numerous patents for developing practical methods for locating likely locations of the deep morphological nodes most likely to indicate the presence of abiogenic hydrocarbons.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] His methods and technologies are used to this day by geophysicists to locate deep hydrocarbon deposits.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The presence of methane on Saturn's moon Titan and in the atmospheres of Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune is cited as evidence of the formation of hydrocarbons without biological intermediate forms, for example by Thomas Gold.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] (Terrestrial natural gas is composed primarily of methane).
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some comets contain massive amounts of organic compounds, the equivalent of cubic kilometers of such mixed with other material; for instance, corresponding hydrocarbons were detected during a probe flyby through the tail of Halley's Comet in 1986.
[src:acidobacteriota/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Drill samples from the surface of Mars taken in 2015 by the Curiosity Rover's Mars Science Laboratory revealed the presence of benzene and propane in 3 billion-year-old rock samples taken from Gale Crater.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthopleuribacter-pedis] Colonies on marine agar are circular, smooth and yellow in color.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthopleuribacter-pedis] *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* are found on marine agar at a temperature of 15–30 °C (optimally at 30 °C), and grows at a pH of 5–9 (optimally at pH 7–8).
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthopleuribacter-pedis] *Acanthopleura*, a genus of shellfish; N.L. masc. n.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthopleuribacter-pedis] *Acanthopleuribacter*, a rod from *Acanthopleura*, referring to the isolation of the first strain from the chiton *Acanthopleura japonica*.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthopleuribacter-pedis] The genus contains a single species namely *A. pedis* ( Fukunaga *et al.* 2008, sp. nov.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthopleuribacter-pedis] (Type species of the genus).; L. gen. n.
[src:acidobacteriota/acanthopleuribacter-pedis] Members of the phylum Acidobacteria are ubiquitous in various environments.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidimicrobiia] The ***Acidimicrobiia*** are a class of Actinomycetota, in which three families, eight genera, and nine species have been described, *Acidimicrobium ferrooxidans* is the type species of the order.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidimicrobiia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:acidobacteriota/acidithiobacillales] Acidithiobacilia is part of the acidophilic bacteria family.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidithiobacillales] Acidithiobacilia's metabolic activity is important because it is relied on for an approach for metal recovery from ores, called microorganism-mediated biohydrometallurgy.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidithiobacillales] Acidithiobacilia and family of bacteria are active players in the sulfur and iron biogeochemical cycles in extremely acidic environments and drivers of the leaching of mineral ores contributing to acid rock/mine drainage and industrial bioleaching.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:acidobacteriota/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
